Intuition
after looking at this problem i realized it is a sliding window pattern , and window size is not fixed , for this question my thinking is i will find the maximum possible substring in which with k replacements i can get longest substring with same letter , for this my formula is calculate the most frequent character of the substring , then check length of substring - most_frequent if it is less than or equal to k valid case, otherwise , remove characters from frequency map

Approach
low = 0
result = 0
max_freq = 0
freq = {}

traverse the string , add characters into frequency map :
for high in range (len(s)):
add characters into frequency map
calculate the most frequent character

calculate length of substring

check for invalid condition ,
while length of substring - most frequent character > k:
remove elements from frequency map
move low by +1
recount length of substring
calculate length of substring
find max possible length and store it in result
return result

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)

Space complexity:
O(1)

Code
class Solution:
    def characterReplacement(self, s: str, k: int) -> int:
        low = 0
        result = 0 
        freq = {}
        max_freq = 0

        for high in range(len(s)):
            freq[s[high]] = freq.get(s[high] , 0) + 1
            max_freq = max(max_freq , freq[s[high]])
            window_length = high - low + 1

            while window_length - max_freq > k:
                freq[s[low]] -= 1
                if freq[s[low]] == 0:
                    del freq[s[low]]
                low += 1
                window_length = high - low + 1
            
            length = high - low + 1
            result = max(result , length)
        return result
